Honestly — yes, for your grade it is.

Here's why:

The rubric specifically requires (Section D & M):

Requirement	Without FIES	With FIES
Use a dataset (CSV/Excel/JSON)	❌ No external dataset	✅ 41,544-row CSV
Train a ML model	⚠️ Trains on user's own data only	✅ Trains on real PH government data
Submit a dataset file	❌ Nothing to submit	✅ fies_data.csv
Submit a model file (.pkl)	✅ forecaster.pkl	✅ fies_model.pkl
Display analytical output	✅ Forecast chart	✅ Benchmark comparison
Your existing ML (forecaster.py) trains on the user's own expense history — the panel might question whether that really counts as "using a dataset" since it's just the user's personal records.

The FIES model trains on an actual external CSV dataset — which is clearly what the rubric means by "use a dataset."

For your presentation it also makes a strong point:

"We used the PSA Family Income and Expenditure Survey — 41,544 real Filipino households — to train a model that benchmarks our users' spending against national data."

That sounds much more impressive than just forecasting based on your own history.

So keep it. It directly covers the 25% ML criterion and gives you a clear dataset to submit.

